@solangeknowles made an appearance at the New York Public Library @nypl earlier this week for a special honor. Knowles, along with fellow creative peers that included actress @im.angelabassett, journalist @nikolehannahjones, literary critic @henrylouisgates and novelist and writer Edwidge Danticat, were the selected honorees at the @schomburgcenter for Research in Black Culture's Centennial Gala, marking 100 years of the institution. Founded by Arturo Alfonso Schomburg in 1926, the Schomburg Center has served as a significant resource in the preservation of decades of Black history.
For the evening, the multidisciplinary artist wore a full look from @isseymiyakeofficial's Fall 2026 collection that included a flowing blazer and belted maxi skirt layered over pristinely tailored trousers. The ensemble was a smart and sophisticated take on classic evening suiting that was also quintessentially Solange.
📸: Ilya Savenok/Getty

Each spring, celebrities clamor to interpret a new dress code for the Met Gala. But while the theme is everchanging, the bar for theater, drama and (hopefully) creativity remains consistently high. Clothes can take hundreds of hours to make, not to mention months to design. Dress well and your efforts could become part of fashion history — helping to define the landmark event for years to come.
As the first Monday in May approaches, we take a look back at the event’s sartorial hall of fame — from @cher’s crystalline @bobmackie dress in 1985 to @badgalriri’s yolk-colored @guopei gown in 2015.
📸: Andrew Kelly/Reuters; Mario Anzuoni/Reuters; Rabbani and Solimene/WireImages/Getty Images; Ron Galella/Getty Images; Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images; Patrick McMullan/Getty Images; Taylor Hill/FilmMagic/Getty Images; Neilson Barnard/Getty Images; Michael Buckner/Variety/Getty Images; Angela Weiss/AFP/Getty Images; Kevin Mazur/Getty Images;

@isseymiyakeofficial is taking its signature heat-baked pleating technique far beyond clothing, turning it into furniture and lighting that feel like garments frozen mid-motion. Known for “baking” folds into fabric using heat-resistant thread, the brand now applies that same sculptural magic to chairs, tables, and the O Series lamps, airy designs that look like dresses draped over glowing wire frames. Created with Ambientec and Atelier Oï, the lamps blur the line between fashion and functional art.⁠
⁠
The real twist comes from the process itself. Artistic director Satoshi Kondo repurposed discarded pleating paper, transforming it into benches and colorful brick-like structures in collaboration with Ensamble Studio. What started as show seating evolved into full-fledged design pieces, proving Miyake’s innovation isn’t just wearable, it’s livable. At this rate, a fully pleated home doesn’t sound that far off.

@maxandco elevates everyday dressing with the ease of the perfect in-between.
Not so chic that you’re overdressed when plans suddenly change, but also never too safe. Spring/Summer 2026 lands right in that sweet spot with chic tailoring, versatile outerwear, playful dresses, and small hits of colour that wake everything up. The result is a wardrobe that can handle office hours, dinner plans, weekends away, and whatever else is on your calendar.
